I know there have been quite a few answers to this question. However,
with no offense meant to anyone, quite a few seems like a very stupid
way to solve this problem. Some answers pointed it out. Yes, there is
a builtin alias thingie in TF. And it works really well. They are not world
specific, however. Not completely built in either. It's a part of the
TF standard library of functions. namely the "alias.tf" file. Since there
seems to be some confusion in the usage, I thought I'd help out and
give some examples.

First, add this line to your .tfrc:
  /require alias.tf

Then you can put aliases in your files like this:
  /alias cc cast cure critic

This will allow you to typ "cc" just like a normal MUD command, without any
leading slash ("/").
If you want to let your aliases take arguments, these are available as %X,
where X is the argument number you want to use. 0 or * means all arguments.
Note that "all arguments" can also mean nothing at all, if no arguments
are given.

Some examples:

  ;; This will let you use the /alias command without the leading slash
  ;; Like:  "alias tr cast tremor" instead of "/alias tr cast tremor"
  ;; NOTE:  although this works when while connected, files that are loaded
  ;;        still have to use /alias, since aliases only expand at the time
  ;;        a line is sent to the MUD

  /alias alias   /alias %*
  /alias unalias /unalias %*

  ;; Note that the "smi" alias below will work both with and without argument
  ;; "smi x" will send "smile x" and "smi" will send "smile"
  /alias smi smile %*

  ;; An example that will always adress a person by name
  ;; Assumes your MUD has a command "TELL X MSG" to tell person X the text MSG
  ;; "ntell Ben go north" will send "tell Ben Ben go north"
  /alias ntell tell %1 %*

  ;; Another example: get something from a container
  ;; "gf X Y" sends "get X from Y"
  /alias gf get %1 from %2

  ;; This is an example on how to check for an argument
  ;; It checks it it's a typo of "say" or a abbreviation of "satisfied"
  ;; by assuming "satisfied" wants no arguments, and "say" does
  /alias sat /if /test "%*" =~ "" %; \
             /then emote looks satisfied.%; \
             /else say %*%; \
             /endif



Well... That's all folks! I hope this helps someone, somewhat.

  /Mikael


