Yes, but that keybinding will also expand when you don't want it to,
for example when typing "succubus".  You can input a literal (uninterpreted)
"cc" by typing ^Vcc, but it's still inconvenient.  I suggest a macro:

  /def cc = /send cast 'cure crit' %*

which you use like this:

  /cc someone

If you really don't like that leading "/", use an alias instead.
/alias handles arguments just like macros do, using % expansions in the
body (so that replacement posted by David Moore is not needed, and is
actually less flexible).  Just remember that there is no "=" between
the name and the body.

  /alias cc  /send cast 'cure crit' %*

which you use like this:

  cc someone

Note the use of /send in the alias body.  If you used an implicit send,
like this:

  /alias cc  cast 'cure crit' %*

then "cast" would also be checked for alias expansion (actually, SEND hooks).
The explicit "/send" bypasses the recursive alias check.  It probably would
not have been a problem in the previous example, but the next one would
loop forever if it did not use /send:

  /alias run  /send run away

