You apparently tried to do something like this:

  /if wh thief%; /then ...

The command "wh thief" is considered true if tf can send the command
(i.e., there is a current connected socket), otherwise it is false.
Usually, this is not what the user intended; users usually mistakenly
use this form to test the result of a command on the server, which is
NOT what this form does.  There are 2 reasons for this:  tf can not
know what (if any) response is generated by a server command; and
waiting for a response would block tf indefinitely.  See: "/help /if".

If you really do want to test connectivity, you can use this form to avoid
the warning:

  /if /send wh thief%; /then ...

