Since 3.5 alpha 21 (10/12/96), adjacent repeated input lines are not saved
in history.  This achieves nearly the same effect.

So, given your example above, your history will contain:

  e
  n
  eat flesh
  who
  e
  w
  e
  n

and searching backward for "e" would find "e" 2 times (instead of 4)
before finding "eat flesh".  This example is not particularly realistic;
you know there are going to be a lot of "e" lines in history, so you would
use "ea" as the search prefix and find "eat flesh" with one esc-p.

Also, I just made a simple change to 3.5 beta 2 (unreleased) so that 
it only finds line for which the prefix is a proper prefix, not an exact
match (since if you typed the whole line exactly, there's no need to search,
just hit return).  In the example above, after typing "e", a single esc-p
would find "eat flesh", since the exact "e" matches are ignored.

