> Now the def for it is
>  /def -p1 -mregexp -t'(.*) enters' heal = clw %p1
>  which works fine.

I suggest using a more specific regexp:

   /def -p1 -mregexp -t'^([^ ]+) enters' heal = clw %p1

The first "^" matches the beginning of the line, so you don't trigger
on "joe says 'bob enters.'"  The "[^ ]+" matches one or more non-spaces.

> But I'm looking for a way to turn it on and off.
> 
> What i would liked to have done is
> 
> /def healon =  /def -p1 -mregexp -t'(.*) enters' heal = clw %p1
> /def healoff = /undef heal
> 
> But the first one (healon) interprets the %p1 to be part of its define,

This is basic substitution.  For each level of evaluation nesting you
want to protect the %, add another %.

  /def healon =  /def -p1 -mregexp -t'^([^ ]+) enters' heal = clw %%p1

See /help evaluation, substitution.

