If you do do this, then make sure you give all your trigs names.
I know someone who played a mud that crashed a lot.
His /addworld had a macro file on the end with trigs in it.
The trigs were unnamed, [ eg /trig *died* = get all from corpse ]
The defines in that file remain active even when the world it belongs to
  no longer is.
Now, bcs the trig has no name, when you reconnect to that world, and the
  macro file is re-loaded, all the standard macros are redefined, but the
 trigs are assumed to be new trigs, and both the old and new ones remain.
A few goes of this and you end up with thousands of trigs all catching the
 same thing. And that slows everything down and is likely to get other
 users really @*#$ed at you.
So give your trigs names [ eg /def -t'*died*' corpse = get all from corpse
  or I guess there is a method using /trig for it too, but I don't use it ]
 that way you only have one copy loaded at a time

I'm not really sure on a good way of doing /addchar tho'

I would suggest something like:
/addworld -T'lp' bobmud bob.bobnet.net 1234
/def bill = /world bobmud%;bill%;password%;/load bill.tf
/def john = /world bobmud%;john%;password%;/load john.tf

The only problem being that i suspect the name will get sent be4 the
connecting is established, in which case it may be worth setting up a hook 
for it.
I cant remeber the define for a hook on connection, see /help hooks, but
 I think it is CONNECT:
/addworld -T'lp' bobmud bob.bobnet.net 1234
/def bill = /world bobmud%;/set name=bill%;/set passwd=password
/hook CONNECT = /send %name%;/send %passwd%;/load ~/tf-macros/%name

I'm not sure is that will work, but give it a try.


