Duckie wrote:
> 
> /world
> % Connection to Avatar in progress.

At this point, an unconnected socket to Avatar exists, but it is not
your current socket.  Your current socket is the same now as it was
before this command; if you had no current socket before, you still
have no current socket.  If the connection to Avatar eventually
completes, then Avatar will become your current socket (assuming you
haven't modified the default CONNECT hook).

> /dc
> % dc: no current socket

/dc with no arguments operates on the current socket.  Avatar is not
current, and you apparently had no other current socket.  To close
Avatar's socket, use "/dc Avatar".

> /world
> % connect: socket to Avatar already exists

If a socket to a world is connected, /world will bring it into the
foreground with /fg; if not, /world will open a socket with /connect.
Since Avatar is not connected, the /fg fails (calling /fg directly
would have told you "not connected to Avatar").  Since a socket to
Avatar is open, the /connect tells you that.  At this point, you
can either wait for the connection to complete, or close the socket
with "/dc Avatar".

