Susan Dittmar wrote:
> 
> I'm playing several characters with different behaviour. This means if 
> one of them would try to behave like the other one, he would most 
> probably die in his next fight. So the triggers must be different for the 
> different characters.
> 
> Of course there is the possibility to have several configuration files 
> for the different characters, and I'm using this. 
> 
> Now I'd like to log in with two such characters in parallel.
> They have some triggers and commands in common, like a trigger on 
> "you are hungry", but they possess different food sources, so the 
> resulting commands must be different.
> 
> If I use the -w<world> flag, I can still seperate the triggers. But I'd 
> like to be able to feed my characters by command, like /eat. If I define 
> a trigger /def -t'you are hungry' -w<character1> eat = <command1> and a 
> trigger /def -t'you are hungry' -w<character2> eat = <command2>, the 
> second definition will overwrite the first and I cannot feed the first 
> character.

Method 1: use an /if based on ${world_name} or ${character_name}:

  /def -t"you are hungry" eat = \
      /if (${world_name} =~ "world1") \
          command1%; \
      /elseif (${world_name} =~ "world2") \
          command2%; \
      /endif

Method 2: write a macro for each world, and a "master" macro that calls
the macro for the correct world:

  /def -wworld1 -t"you are hungry" eat_world1 = command1
  /def -wworld2 -t"you are hungry" eat_world2 = command2
  /def eat = /eat_${world_name} %*

The second method is more flexible:  The world-specific macros can each
be defined in world-specific files to organize them better, and the
master macro doesn't need to explicitly name each world.  Both methods
will execute the appropriate command when triggered by "you are hungry"
or invoked with "/eat [<arguments>]".

> Another problem: Whenever a trigger in the background world reacts, the 
> commands sent by this trigger are sent to the foreground world. Is there 
> a way to stop this behaviour without using /send -w<character> <command> 
> everywhere? (I'm using tf-35a20, installing another version would not 
> cause much trouble for me, if it helps ...)

I think you're confused.

The Current world is used for the destination of all simple text
commands, ${world_name}, etc.  The Foreground world is the Current
world for commands entered on the command line.  But when a macro is
triggered in any world (Foreground or Background), that world becomes
the Current world for executing the macro.

The only thing that could explain what you saw is if your macro calls
/repeat or /quote without -w:  then the Current world for the
subcommand is whatever world happens to be Foreground when it's time to
execute.  Use -w to make the subcommand's Current world the same as
what was Current when /repeat or /quote was called.

See: /help sockets

