> Which is not at all what I expected (or wanted!). Is this behaviour  
> correct? Why?

	Yes.  /repeat format is "/repeat <switches> <command>"
Your command for the first repeat is the rest of the line.  So, tf
executes the entire command, in sequence.  First the test is echoed,
the second repeat is issued, with a delay, and the end is echoed.
After the delay for the second /repeat expires, that repeat executes
it's command to echo test2.  Think of it as a queue of commands, where
the middle /repeat enqueues a new command _after_ everything else
is already enqueued.  As long as you have the second /repeat in
the middle, anything it does will always happen after the /echo end.


> And lastly, how should I go about making a /delay  
> <seconds> macro? Is is impossible?

	Yes.  /repeat does that.  Like I said, as long as the commands
that /repeat issues don't add more commands to the queue, it'll work.
/repeat -<delayseconds> 1 /echo test1%; /echo test2 %; /echo end


	Maybe it would help us if you told us why you feel you need
a second /repeat in the middle?

