According to Urban Nilsson:
> > /repeat -1 1 /echo test%; /repeat -1 1 /echo test2%; /echo end
> 
> produces the output:
> test
> end
> < a 1 second delay >
> test2
> 
> Which is not at all what I expected (or wanted!). Is this behaviour  
> correct? Why? [...]

(Please note that everything here is untested.)
Yes, it's correct.
As said in other mail, you are starting three commands after one second.
One prints "test", one starts a new delayed command, and one echoes "end".
Hence you see "test", then nothing because you just start a timer, then
you see "end". One second later the timer executes its command, and you
get "test2".

Maybe try something like:
/repeat -1 1 /echo test%; /repeat -1 1 /echo test2%%; /echo end

Here you start two commands:
/repeat -1 1 /echo test
/repeat -1 1 /echo test2%; /echo end

and this produces:
test
<one seconds delay>
test2
end

Which probably is closer to what you wanted. This is due to the extra "%"
in my version. "%%;" gets evaluated, and turned into "%;", saving the
conversion to a command delimiter until the next loop of evaluation,
namely when the second timer expires and runs it's command.

> [...] And lastly, how should I go about making a /delay  
> <seconds> macro? Is is impossible?

Yes, it's impossible to delay the evaluation of a macro.
So, no, you can't create a delay macro. However, you could use the same
technic I used in your little example above. Define a "timer" (a delayed 
one shot repeat) that executes two commands: your first "real" command,
and a new timer. Let that second timer in turn define two commands:
your seconds "real" command, and a new timer. That timer can in turn....
Get the idea? :-)  The problem is you get a LOT of percentage signs
between commands, in the end, and it ends up pretty unreadable.

I guess maybe one could make a variable that holds a string, containing
a number (the delay), and a command, then a new number, and a new command,
etc, and make a macro automatically set up the first command with a timer
with the specified delay, and then let that timer execute the command,
and set up the next timer. This would be self sustaining until the string
is empty. I can't really think of how you would do that, though. And you
would only be able to run one such delayed chain of commands at a time.

I hope I've been of some help, at least... :-)

  /Mikael


