> most recently opened log file.

> /def -F -hconnect logworld_input = /log -i \
> 	~/logs/$[ftime("%m%d%y",time())].%1log

Use a send hook and fwrite() (which was added in 3.5 beta 1, get it if
you don't have it):

  /def -hSEND log_world_input = \
      /let filename=~/logs/${world_name}.$[ftime("%y%m%d",time())].log%; \
      /test fwrite(filename, {*})

If you want "> " on the beginning of each line, change that last line to:

      /test fwrite(filename, strcat("> ", {*}))

Also note I changed the format of the log file name to "WORLD.YYMMDD.log".
World is first because IMO it's most important, and the YYMMDD date order
makes them sort chronologically.

