Well... Loading is easy... Just write a file in your favourite editor:

/alias   alias /alias %*
/unalias unalias /unalias %*
/alias   hello  smile%;say Hello, %*

etc...

Then go into TF and invoke "/load filename". :-)

Note that even though I like to be able to define my aliases without the
leading slash while in a MUD, I still have to use the slash when defining
aliases in a file, since it's not something I send to the MUD, and can
therefor not be intercepted by the SEND hook that an alias sets up.

As for saving, I have never been one for trusting any program of TF's type
to write anything even remotely sane to a file, when it comes to saving
stuff I did. I always write my files myself. Just shell out of TF,
invoke an editor on the file, and fix whatever you like, go back into TF and
/load the file. That way you get your aliases in the right file too,
if you like to (as I do), load a diffrent file with different aliases for
every MUD.

