In a glob pattern, "*" matches 0 or more occurances of any character.
To match the end of the line that you omitted, you must use "*".

To match a literal "*", you must use "\*" (this is described in "/help
patterns").

To get a literal "\" in a quoted option string, you must use "\\";
this means to get "\*" you must use "\\*".

To get a literal "\" in a nested macro body, you must use "\\";
this means to get "\\*", you must use "\\\\*".

Every time you type "autoflee <name> <race>", your alias will define a
new trigger, but will not delete the old one.  If you give the trigger
a name, the new trigger will replace the old trigger with the same name.

With all these changes, the definition looks like this:

/alias autoflee \
    /def -mglob -t"\\\\*%1 the %2\\\\* begins some strange*" flee_trigger = \
        flee%;\
        exit%;\
        targ %1%;\
        /echo *** TARGET IS NOW %1 ***

