A command is terminated by the end of a logical line.  When /load'ing
from a file, a trailing '\' joins the next physical line to the current
physical line to create a long logical line; an alternate way to think
of this is that when /load'ing a command is terminated by a line that
doesn't end with '\'.

/def is just a command that takes some arguments, which are interpreted
as: "[options] [name][=body]".  So it defines a macro named tt_test,
with the body

  /def huhu=/echo huhu%;/def haha=/echo haha

When a macro body is executed, tf scans for '%;', which separates
commands, multiple '%'s, which are replaced with one fewer '%', and
several other special strings.  Everything else is just text (at this
stage).  So when tt_test is executed, tf sees:

  <first command>%;<second command>

where <first command> happens to be

  /def huhu=/echo huhu

and <second command> happens to be

  /def haha=/echo haha

...so macros huhu and haha are both defined.

Now the problem is, what if you really want '%;' to be inside <first command>,
not interpeted as a separator?  Use '%%;'.  The '%%' will be replaced with
'%', and the ';' is just text.  So, if you had changed the body of tt_test
to this:

  /def huhu= /echo huhu%%; /def haha=/echo haha

Then when it was executed, tf would see:

  <first command>

Where <first command> happens to be

  /def huhu= /echo huhu%; /def haha=/echo haha

Notice how the '%%' changed to '%'.

