I'll explain a slightly more complex macro that defines A and B.
A defines A1 and A2, and B defines B1 and B2.  Each macro echoes.

It's often easiest to think inside-out when writing nested macros.  First
decide what you want the deepest level to do:  define A1, A2, B1, and B2:

  /def A1 = /echo This is A1

  /def A2 = /echo This is A2

  /def B1 = /echo This is B1

  /def B2 = /echo This is B2

At the next level, you want to define A so it defines A1 and A2; and
define B so it defines B1 and B2.  Since there are no special characters
in the commands above, you only need to separate them with '%;':

  /def A =\
    /echo This is A%;\
    /def A1 = /echo This is A1%;\
    /def A2 = /echo This is A2

  /def B=\
    /echo This is B%;\
    /def B1 = /echo This is B1%;\
    /def B2 = /echo This is B2

At the next level, you want to define example so it defines A and
B.  So you add a '%' to every sequence of '%'s in the two commands
above so they won't be interpreted at this level, then stick the commands
together with '%;' between them:

  /def example =\
    /echo This is example%;\
    /def A =\
      /echo This is A%%;\
      /def A1 = /echo This is A1%%;\
      /def A2 = /echo This is A2%;\
    /def B=\
      /echo This is B%%;\
      /def B1 = /echo This is B1%%;\
      /def B2 = /echo This is B2


