Hi, all.

I'm wondering if there's a way I can time a period more precisely
than one second.  The context is a simplistic in-session ping macro,
along the lines of:

/set ping_times=
/set max_ping=0

/def -i ping = \
  /send emote checks the ping times.%;\
  /set ping_start=$(/time @)

/def -i -ag -t'You emote: Socrates checks the ping times.' \
catch_ping = \
  /if (ping_start > 0) \
    /let ping_end=$(/time @) %;\
    /let pt=$[ping_end - ping_start] %;\
    /if (pt > max_ping) \
      /set max_ping=%{pt}%;\
    /endif %;\
    /unset ping_start %;\
    /set ping_times=%{ping_times} %{pt} %;\
    /let sumtimes=$(/sum_list %{ping_times}) %;\
    /let numtimes=$(/num_items %{ping_times}) %;\
    /if (numtimes > 0) \
      /let avgping=$[sumtimes / numtimes] %;\
    /else \
      /let avgping=%{ping_times} %;\
    /endif %;\
    /echo Ping time: %{pt}; avg\/max = %{avgping}\/%{max_ping} %;\
  /endif

/def -i sum_list = \
  /set sum=0 %;\
  /while ({#}) \
    /set sum=$[sum + {1}] %;\
    /shift %;\
  /done %;\
  /echo %{sum} %;\
  /unset sum

/def -i num_items = /echo %#


The basic idea is that you do "/ping", which sends an emote to the 
mud, and a trigger captures the output.  It's only precise to the
second, though, as "/time" gives the current time in seconds.  
Any possibility of getting something more precise?

