Right.  Bindings don't currently work with -w or -T.  One thing you can
do is have one binding which calls a macro which does an /if check.  But
then you couldn't do the same kind of easy checking as with -T.

However, you can do something like this:


/def -B'F9' bind_who =\
    /let pat=SECRIT CODE WORDZ $[rand()] who who who%;\
    /let pri=$[maxpri - 10]%;\
    /def -T'tiny.moo' -p%pri -t'%pat' _bind_who1 =\
	/purge _bind_who?%%;\
	@who%;\
    /def -T'tiny.mush' -p%pri -t'%pat' _bind_who2 =\
	/purge _bind_who?%%;\
	who%;\
    /def -p$[pri-1] -t'%pat' _bind_whoX =\
	/purge _bind_who?%%;\
	/echo \% No who command set for this world type.
    /trigger %pat


Which will send '@who' to moos and 'who' to mushs.  And spew a friendly
error message on other worlds.



