Actually there are two of us working on a Win32 port.  One route is to try and build 
around the Cygnus Gnu-Win32 GCC Environment.  This is the route the is probably
the easiest and the quickest, but it also requires about a 10 meg download of a 
pretty buggy Run-Time/Development environment and a difficult configuration.  
To make matters worse, the CygWin32 platform is still under heavy development 
itself, so version to version stability is a little weak. 

The approach I am taking is to modify as little as I have to and make it a native 
Win32 Console Application that can be compiled in MSVC, Borland C, Watcom, or
Metrowerks.  This is a more arduous task, but hopefully after I get it working 
once I will be able to give the modifications to Ken and let him decide if he would
like to add the changes into the "Official" version.  That will be at his discretion 
of course.  At the moment, my VC port is still very rough, the hardest part being 
finding the proper include files and of course creating a proper config.h.  The 
other task has been getting the Windows TCP sockets mapped to the UNIX style
calls that TF uses.  Not too terribly ugly, but time consuming.  I don;t expect 
to have anything releasable for a couple of months since it is a part time project
that is going hand in hand with another TF related project of porting TF to the 
Java Virtual MAchine.  Not as an applet but as a command line Java Applicaiton.
This started off as a play project, but the more I work with it the more 
convinced I am that this is the way to go to gain additional platform support as 
this would instantly add Win3.x Win32 (95/NT) MacOS and of course Java based
NC's.

