At first you'll have to define a prompt hook that reads your hitpoints
into a variable. On each prompt the macro /checkheal is then called.
The problem is normally to wait until one try to heal has been fulfilled.
Just look below and look at how that /checkheal works.

/def -mregexp -h'PROMPT ^.* (-?[0-9]*)H ([0-9]*)M.*' readprompt =\
 /set hit %P1 %; /set mana %P2 %; /checkheal %; /prompt %*

;; Initializations for autoheal. lhit = threshold when a heal is cast.
;; %healing indicates whether a try to heal is running and not fully
;; resolved
/set lhit 260
/set healing 0

/def checkheal = /if ((hit <= lhit)&(!healing)) /healme %; /endif

/def healme = \
       /if (!healing) \
           /set healing 1 %; \
           /send cast 'heal' glod %;\
           /send tell glod . %; \
           /def -1 -p2 -F -mglob -t'*You try to tell*' = /set healing 0 %;\
       /endif

While healing is 1 no more heal-spells will be launched. Directly after
the casting I send an auto-tell, which produces in my mud the output
'You try to tell yourself something'. The client can trigger on that text
and can unset healing again. If you dont use that trigger timing you get
the problem that the client would normally launch several heal actions,
especially when fight lagged through special actions, for example a kick.

Hope that helps,
