As long as all the macros are named (always worth doing anyway), and are
all defined in each file, you don't need to /undef them first, and tf
will override them. But, especially if you change worlds often, this is
going to be fairly slow to load them all each time.

Instead, I would suggest something along the lines of the following. Of
course, this may not be suitable for your situation, in which case just
ignore me! In particular, I haven't mentioned variables which are
world-specific.

1. Name all the macros uniquely, probably as <macro-name>_<world-name>.
2. For all macros with triggers, you can simply define them with the
   -w<world-name> switch, and all will be hoopy.
3. Any other macros -- or macros with triggers which you also want to
   call -- you'll have to write a wrapper, along the (untested :) lines
   of
	/def foo = /eval /foo_${world_name} %*
   which will call the correct macro for the world you are currently in,
   assuming you've named your macros as in step 1.

