/def -t'line 3' trig1_3 = /teststate 2 %; /newstate 0 %; things

/def -t'line 1' trig2_1 = /teststate 0 %; /newstate 10
/def -t'line 2' trig2_2 = /teststate 10 %; /newstate 11
/def -t'line 3' trig2_3 = /teststate 11 %; /newstate 0 %; things

There are two obvious problemas. The first, this is way too verbose. 
The second, how will /teststate stop the parent macro (the "trig" 
macros)?

I considered reducing all commands to a simple /state command:

/def -t'line 1' trig1_1 = /state 0 1
/def -t'line 2' trig1_2 = /state 1 2
/def -t'line 3' trig1_3 = /state 2 0 %; things

That's way better. But it has the same problem /teststate has, and 
introduces a new problem: it is too cryptic. :-) Well, it *looks* 
cryptic to me. :-)

The problem would be better solved, but reducing the flexibility (the 
ability to use states for other purpuses) by writting a wrapper macro:

/mtrig -t'line 1' trig1
/mtrig -t'line 2' trig1
/mtrig -t'line 3' trig1 = things

In this case, the /mtrig would write the appropriate state-aware 
macros, and would take care with multiple triggers. The problem here 
is that you won't be able to do actions at each trigger line. The 
solution:

/mtrig -t'line 1' trig1 = things
/mtrig -t'line 2' trig1 = things
/emtrig -t'line 3' trig1 = things

In either case, the macros names would not be "trig1". So, the user 
would have a *lot* of trouble trying to undefine or redefine it.

The last problem is... that I'm not sure how I'll proceed if the 
later lines *are not* triggered. Sigh... 

