My /take is actually coded into the MUX I go on, as 'ed'.  The grabber:

/def -i -p100 -ag -t'FugueEdit > *' FugueEdit = /grab %-2

The macros:

edit1: $ed */*:setq(0,[switch(%0,me,%#,here,%l,[locate(%#,%0,*)])]);@set/quiet
me=vn:%q0;@set/quiet me=vr:%1;@pemit %#=FugueEdit > &%1 %q0=[get(%q0/%1)]
edit2: $ed *:@switch %0=*/*,,{@vr me=%0;@pemit %#=FugueEdit > &%0
%vn=[get(%vn/%0)]}
edit3: $ed:@pemit %#=FugueEdit > &%vr %vn=[get(%vn/%vr)]
edit4: $ng *:setq(0,[switch(%0,me,%#,here,%l,[locate(%#,%0,*)])]);@pemit
%#=FugueEdit > @name %q0=[fullname(%q0)]

These may require some adjusting for MUSH.  Basically, "ed obj/attr" will 
edit the attribute on the object.  "ed attr" will edit the attribute on 
the last object used in the editor.  "ed" will edit the last attribute 
edited.  "ng obj" will edit the object's name.

The output with ed me/testattr:

FugueEdit > &testattr #9527=This is the attribute's contents.

Hope this helps.  As I said, I've never needed to repeat this -- it 
catches every time.

