>                 /set rest $[substr(temp_str, $[strchr(temp_str,",")+1])]%;\
>                 /set temp_str $[strcat(prev,"%;",rest)] %;\
>         /done %;\
>         /eval %{temp_str}
> 
> 
> Is this the most efficient way to do this? or is there some way to change
> the builtin delimeter in tf? (nothing in /help suggests you can).

Well, your loop could store the result of strchr() in a variable instead
of calling it 3 times, and there's no need for both temp_str and rest;
but to answer your real question, no, there's no way to change the command
terminator.

> Is there any way to have tf read all my input and if it has a new delimeter
> character /eval the line after changing the new delimeters to %;'s? e.g I
> type in 'command;command2;command3' tf would parse that into
> /eval command%;command2%;command3 based solely on the fact it had ';' in it?
> 
> (yes i realize this may cause problems in tells and such, I'm willing to
> deal with that if there is any way to do it....any ideas?)

If you're just trying to save typing on the command line, an alternative
solution is:
  /def -b; semicolon = /input %%;

