Didn't understand your example, lemme try to explain it with a lil macro
of my own:

/def track = \
    /if /ismacro doTrack%; /then \
        /echo -e %%% Autotracking disabled.%;\
        /undef doTrack%;\
    /else  \
        /echo -e %%% Autotracking enabled.%;\
        /def -mregexp -t"^You see your quarry's trail head \
        (east|west|north|south|down|up) from here!" doTrack = %%{P1} %;\
    /endif

And look at the two % signs on the last line, the doTrack macro is
nested within the track macro, so if you use %{P1} in stead of %%{P1},
and you call the track macro, it wants to fill in the value for %{P1}
while defining the doTrack macro. In this case, the %{P1} doesn't exist,
so the def inside the def would define the macro w/o the %{P1}.

If you call the track macro the way it's defined here, and type /list
doTrack, you see something like this:

% 294: /def -p1 -mregexp -t'^You see your quarry\'s trail head 
(east|west|north|south|down|up) from here!' doTrack = %{P1}

Regularly, you'll have to add an extra % sign for every level you nest a
macro in another macro. It is necessary for global variables as well,
I'm rewriting this track stuff now, and it uses a global variable: (It's
an incomplete macro, but usable as an example)

/def trackTest = \
    /def -mregexp -t"^You see your quarry's trail head \
        (east|west|north|south|down|up) from here!" doTrack = %%{P1} %;\
    /def -t"You suddenly lose track of your quarry!" targetDead = \
        /echo %%% Aaaargh! Your track target is dead!%;\
    /def -t"You have lost your quarry's trail!!" trackAgain = \
        track %%trackTarget% %;\

Again, on the last line, you see the two % signs in %%trackTarget%. And
again, if I would write only one % sign there, it would fill in the
value for %trackTarget% in stead of defining the macro with the name of
the variable in it.

The echos in the nested macros echo only 2 % signs in stead of 3 for
similar reasons, can't really explain those though ;P


