Use /quote -S to make the body execute inline; otherwise, the body of
the quote won't execute until after xp_counter is done executing, and
your info will be corrupted.

Use ' instead of !cat:
  	/quote /set savedexp='~/${world_name}/$[playername]%;\

You could optionally make the file contain a tf command, so you can /load it
instead of using /quote to read it (unless you want to be able to use this
file outside of tf too).

Use the builtin ${world_character} instead of your calculated playername
(assuming you define a character name with /addworld).

  /def -mregexp -t'You receive ([0-9]+) experience points.' xp_counter=\
      /load ~/${world_name}/${world_character}%;\
      /set savedexp=$[savedexp+%P1]%;\
      /sys echo "/set savedexp=%savedexp" > ~/${world_name}/${world_character}

Technically, that file name you generate could contain shell metacharacters
which would screw you up.  The complete fix for this is to quote the file
name, and escape any quotes within the file name.  Also, /quote uses /bin/sh,
which usually doesn't understand ~, but the tf function filename() does.

    ...
    /let name=$(/escape ' ~/${world_name}/${world_character})%;\
    /sys echo "/set savedexp=%savedexp" > '$[filename(name)]'


