On Thu, 19 Jun 1997, CyberDemon Erosmachine wrote:

> Why is it, that on all NUTS based code only, for example, "one" and then "two"
> is sent down the socket when I issue the command "/repeat 1 one %; two %; three
> %; four" to TinyFugue (latest version), and not "one", "two", "three", and
> "four"? It works as expected for other MUDs that I have been on :-/

NUTS code is not infallible, to say the least, and generally quite simple
in handling socket i/o. The effect is that when under moderate+ load (10+
active users) the code will lose data waiting on socket, depending on how
fast the system is (which stipulates how fast the code can get to the data
and stick it in the user's buffer). Users are stored in a linked list
(current versions; older versions used a static array), and the list is
iterated over completely, calling FD_ISSET for write OR read conditions on
the socket after a select() call. 

Problem here is that if we have 10 or so active users, all inputting data
at the same time, and we're multiplexing over the sockets linearly, if you
flood your socket - even a short amount of data sent very quicly - NUTS
grabs whatever data is waiting on the socket at that given moment and
moves on to the next user. All sockets have their mask's FD_ZERO'd AFTER
the entire list of users has been processed, as well as new connections to
the system. 

So what's happening? In between the time it does a call to read() on your
socket and FD_ZERO's your socket mask, more data has come in, but never
gets processed. Bad code design. 

The only way to get around it would be to /ptime 1 and then repeat your
experiment - given an average system loaded with 10+ users, it just isn't
fast enough to get to all your data, so slowing your output will
definitely fix your problem.

