Not true.  The background world is "current" (that's the correct term,
not "active") ONLY for any triggers/hooks/variables/etc executed or
evaluated as a direct result of text or events from that background
world.  It is not made current globally "for a second" or any other time
period; it is guaranteed to not affect any other command or variable
you type at the command line or run by a /repeat or /quote.  The only
possible exception is if a background text or event triggers a macro that
explicitly calls /fg, and in that case you get what you ask for.

