This is really a shell question, not related to tf.  But in unix shells,
^Y is usually delayed suspend, similar to ^Z.  You usually bring the
suspended process back into the foreground with the command "fg".

Chris Robinson wrote: 
> I have a similar problem. I start TinyFugue from fvwm2 in an xterm with
> no shell underneath it, and occasionally I hit control-z accidentally,
> and TF tries to suspend, leaving it 'dead'. I can't get it back at all.
> In fact, the only way I can get rid of the process is a SIGKILL (kill
> -9).
> 
> Is there any way I can tell TinyFugue to ignore the ^Z key sequence?

TF will usually detect when the parent process (xterm, in your case) does
not support job control, and will not honor SIGTSTP (the signal generated
by ^Z).  But even when this is not detected, you can resume tf (or any
other suspended process) by sending it a SIGCONT signal.  Real xterms
even have a menu command to do that from ctrl-leftbutton.

