Fade wrote:
> Is there a way to suspend tf in a way that will allow it to continue to
> act on incoming data even while it's still suspended, and not whenever
> it's returned to the foreground? I tried once to first suspend it, then
> use bg to make it a background process rather than a halted one, but I
> don't think it had the effect I was looking for. Also, if there's a way to
> do this, will I then have to do a /recall in order to see any text that
> may have been received while it was in the background?

No.  A TF process can run in "batch" mode without a terminal, or
interactively with a terminal, but the same process can't do both.  A
background process that does tries to do terminal i/o can be made to
behave in one of two ways:  it can block until it regains control of the
terminal by being brought into the foreground, or it can be allowed to
do its i/o, ignoring any other process that is using the terminal at the
moment.  But the process can never know if it is in the background or
foreground, so it can't know when to avoid i/o but continue computing.
(Actually, this could technically be done by splitting tf into two
processes, one that does terminal i/o and one that does everything
else, but it's not worth the effort.)

As someone else already mentioned, the "iscreen" (or just "screen") program
is a good alternative to this problem.

