> I need a macro to keep myself from getting too idle. I only want it to
> check connections that are NOT in the foreground, that way if I 'alt-w' and
> change worlds, the world the idler sends messages to changes also.

Here's what I use, to send an echo to every world when I am idle.  It can
be adapted to serve your needs:

/def chime=\
  /if (idle() > 600) \
    /def chime_=/echo -ah -w%%1 $[ftime("%T", time())] %;\
    /mapcar /chime_ $(/listsockets -s) %;\
    /undef chime_ %;\
  /endif %;\
  /repeat -1:00 1 /chime

and in .tfrc:
/eval /at $[mod(ftime("%H",time())+1,24)]:00:00 /chime

Instead of an echo, you can just send some text.  Also, you should
do a comparison in /chime_ to see if %1 is equal to ${world_name}.  Be
careful of the number of % and $ you use, to ensure evaluation at the proper
times.

And at the same time as defining chime_, you can set up a quick gag of the huh
message, and undef it when you undef chime_.

Be aware that idle() returns the time since you last typed something into
TF, in any world, which may not be what you want (your idle time on each
particular world).  Trigger activation will not affect the idle() time.


