This is what I use for MUSHes with idle timeouts. It's easy, it's simple,
and since you have to activate it by hand for any new world, you have full
control over what world are affected and you can always just use /kill.

/def -i id = \
    /echo %% Idle timeout avoidance started for this world.%; \
    /idle_a

/def -i idle_a = \
    /repeat -w -0:30 1 /idle_b

/def -i idle_b = \
    @pemit me=%; \
    /idle_a


Once logged into a MUSH, I just type /id and then it starts the sequence
that sends an empty @pemit to there once every 30 mins, which doesn't
trigger your activity signal and annoy you needlessly. There's a lot
better ways I'm sure it could be done, I just threw this together in a
second for myself.

