First of all, every library file as a statement like
/~loaded filename.tf

This makes sure it is added to the list of %_loaded_libs.
If you want to use something like require in your own files, you _will_
need to add something like /~loaded filename.tf to your own files
as well.

> 	I know what is happening here, but I find it a pain to deal with. 
> Is there any possibility or getting a ${LOCALTFDIR} set up? And then just 
> add a switch to /require to check it?
> (/require -l tiny.bind)

Sure. The /require macro is defined in the standard tf library file.
You can simple redefine this yourself by putting something like
this in your own .tfrc:

/def -i require = \
	/if (!getopts("l")) /break%;/endif%;\
    /let LIBDIR=$[opt_l ? LOCALTFDIR : TFLIBDIR]%;\
	/expr LIBDIR%;\
	/if /@test _loaded_libs !/ "*{%{1}}*"%; /then \
		/load %{LIBDIR}/%{1}%;\
	/endif

Note: since /require is in the standard library, it may be redifined
in a new releas (e.g. for efficiency purposes).
In that case - using this redefine - you wouldn't be able to use
/require anymore to load the standard library files...

> Patrick

