Here's something I wrote for Tinymuck Fuzzball, that could be adapted
to your purposes.

Usage:
/editprop <object>=<prop>
The string for setting that property is put into the keyboard buffer.
If more than one property is listed, it picks the last one.
 
Expects the mud to output something that looks like this:
(for example) ex me=sex
str /sex:female
1 property listed.
 
e.g. I type: /editprop me=sex (or /editprop me sex)
I get in the keyboard buffer:  @set me=sex:female (and then I can edit it
as I wish).


/def editprop=\
  /if ({#} == 1) \
    /let object=$[substr({1},0,strstr({1},"="))] %;\
    /let prop=$[substr({1},strstr({1},"=")+1)] %;\
  /else \
    /let object=%1 %;\
    /let prop=%2 %;\
  /endif %;\
  /def -aGg -w${world_name} -q -F -mregexp -t"^(int|lok|ref) /?%prop" \
    otherprops_ %;\
  /def -aGg -w${world_name} -q -F -mregexp -t"^str /?%prop" catchprop_=\
    /set grab_prop_=%prop%%PR %;\
  /def -aGg -w${world_name} -1 -t"{*} {property|properties} listed." \
    propdisp_=\
    /grab @set %object=%%grab_prop_ %%;\
    /undef catchprop_ %;\
  ex %object=%prop %;\
  /repeat -10 1 /purge catchprop_ %%; /purge propdisp_ %%;\
    /purge otherprops_ %%; /unset grab_prop_


