/def . = /set tester=$[rand()] %; \
	/def -mregexp -n1 -ag -t\"%{tester}>(.*)\" \
		autoedit=/input %%P1 %; 
	/if ({#} < 1) \
		/send think %{tester}>&%{attr} \
			%{object}=[get(%{object}/%{attr})] %; \
	/elseif (regmatch('(/)',{0})) \
		/set object=%PL %; \
		/set attr=%PR %; \
		/send think %{tester}>&%{attr} \
			%{object}=[get(%{object}/%{attr})] %; \
	/else \
		/set attr=%0 %;\
		/send think %{tester}>&%{attr} \
			%{object}=[get(%{object}/%{attr})] %; \
	/endif

This macro works a lot like the infamous 'fugued' MUSHCode object, but a 
little safer, since nobody can spoof you and make your shell do
embarassing things (like delete all your files or post your passwd file
to alt.2600). It's also got some additional facilities, inspired by 
Sandi Fallon's modifications to the fuged object:

'/. object/attr' grabs attr off object and puts it into your editing line
(whether visual or not), ready to strike 'Enter' and set it again.

'/. attr' grabs attr from the object you most recently edited.

'/.' grabs the last object/attr pair you edited.

Limitations:

If you name your attributes with embedded '/' characters, you'll need to
specify the entire object/attr to get it to work. Also, if you use an
object name that contains a '/', it'll screw up.

If you set yourself TRACE, you can end up with some Funky Stuff.

Either or both of these could probably be steered about with adequate
safeguarding in either the MUCode or the macro, but this has worked rather
well for me for the last few months.

