Note that inside of /alias % subs refer to things given after the alias
command like `action foo' foo would be %1.  And %P2 would be unbound at
this point.  So you need to quote it.  Also, since you are throwing out
the leading and trailing (.*) you can make it a bit faster by just
leaving that part out entirely and let the default non-binding regexp do 
it's thing.  You probably want to allow mixed case rather than forcing
all upper or all lower like you do.  Finally, the original had an
example of `*a human*', so you have to at least allow space as well.  If 
you want to just kill anything including numbers and punctuation change
the [A-Za-Z ] to [^*].

/alias action /def -1 -mregexp -t"\*([A-Za-z ]*)\*" hunt_it = kill %%P1


