triggers should only get applied to complete lines.  the only way to
match against an unterminated prompt is with the prompt hook, afaik.

in any case, at any point when a regexp for a trigger is compared the
'$' means the end of the string with which it's being compared, not a
newline or some sort of mud notion of termination.

`xx.*$' is equivalent pattern matching-wise to `xx'.  As is `^.*xx.*$'.
The only difference is what values %PL and %PR will have in each of
these cases.

Using ^.* can slow things down a fairly large amount.  A trailing .*$
has less of a performance effect, since the inital portion of the regexp
is already guaranteed to be maximal, so it doesn't waste any time
backtracking when completing the .* to the end.

