What part of `matching the null string that end of the input string' is
confusing?  The null string is an empty string, it is not a newline, it
is not any other special character or mud notion of termination.  It's
just a null string, in exactly the same way the ^ matches the null
string at the beginning of the input string.  The null string has no
relationship to the presence of a NUL character traditionally found at
the end of C string, nor does it have any relationship to a NULL
pointer.  It is referring to `null string' in the sense that regexps are 
finite state automata which match strings of symbols from a symbol set.


But don't take my word for it or the occasionally wrong documentation
(which is right in this case), read the regexp/regexp.c file, and note
that quite clearly there is no support for handing a notion of "partial"
lines to the regexp matcher.  The regexp matcher does not use newline as
the end of string match, it uses the NUL of a C string.  That will exist
at any point the regexp code is called.  If you're really want to look
into this, you can write a quick program on top of the regexp package
which sends string in to be matched against the regexp "$".  You'll soon
discover that you can't make any string which won't match that.


You can also find by reading the src/socket.c file and peering at the
handle_socket_input function that handle_socket_line is only called when
a newline has been seen (or the one special case when the connection to
the mud was lost while you had a partial line).  Since
handle_socket_line is the routine responsible for running triggers,
you'll see that a trigger can only be run on a complete line (except the
special disconnect case).  So not only does the regexp package not have
a notion of "$" meaning newline or some sort of other mud termination,
tf still only runs triggers against lines that ended with newline.
Either one of these conditions would be sufficient to make `x.*$' and
`x' the same for trigger patterns, and in tf you've got both.

