There's actually an interesting way to pick a random line from a set of
lines without taking any extra storage.  As you go along you keep track
of a current pick.  You randomly decide to replace the pick with the
line you are now looking at.  Obviously if you did a 50% choice, it'd be
heavily weighted to the latter lines.  But if you pick a 1/N choice to
swap, you'll see that every line ends up with equal chance.  Macro to do 
such:

/def random_line = \
    /let selection=%;\
    /let lines=0%;\
    /quote -S /random_line_ `%*%;\
    /echo %{selection}

/def random_line_ = \
    /test rand(++lines) | (selection:={*})


you can use it the same way as Karen's.  Or if you know you're always
going to be using it on a file, you can add this for a bit more speed,
cutting out an intermediate /quote queue.

/def random_file_line = \
    /let selection=%;\
    /let lines=0%;\
    /quote -S /random_line_ '%*%;\
    /echo %{selection}


