/addworld dummyworld localhost echo
/histsize -wdummyworld 10

/def save_some_vars =\
    /if ({#} != 2) \
	/echo -e \% Usage: save_some_vars PREFIX FILENAME%;\
	/break%;\
    /endif%;\
    /let pattern=^/set %1[^=]*=%;\
    /let file=$[filename({2})]%;\
    /log -wdummyworld %{file}%;\
    /quote -S /save_same_vars_ `/set%;\
    /log -wdummyworld off

/def save_some_vars_ =\
    /if (regmatch(pattern, {*})) \
	/echo -wdummyworld -- %*%;\
    /endif


Or you could just manually turn on logging and use /egrep to help you
weed them out.  In 3.6 you could avoid the /log by using the new
file/queue access routines.  You could use fwrite() now, but that's
slower than logging, since it would open and close the file on every
line.  You could also make save_some_vars_ a bit faster using a single
/test (like _egrep) by using optional args to echo().

Note that the prefix you give to save_some_vars can include regexp
patterns.


To use egrep, /require grep.tf.  And use it like:
/egrep color /set

I personally enjoy using commands like
/wc /egrep smurf /recall 0- Hawkeye*
which seems to hit 5 entries on druidmuck[1].  Of course sticking that
pattern in the /recall would be faster, but where's the fun in that??

