The short answer is /set sub=on or /set sub=full before typing a that line,
or put "/eval" at the beginning of that line.

Jeff <schaller@engr.ukans.edu> wrote:
> Not without making a "macro" (send hook) to /eval everything you type
> before sending it on ...
> /def -h"SEND *" catch_and_eval = /eval /send %*

This works, but "/set sub=full" has the same effect.

"Bjrn Svartengren" <svarten@bank.posten.se> wrote:
> It's still possible to do it without any macro, just escape the % like:
> 
> kill blah\%;fight blah\%;engage stuff
> 
> I do it now and then :)

That's backwards.  If you had sub=on, then those "\"s would escape the
meaning of "%;" and make it literal.

Altpeter Frank <freddy@saarlink.de> wrote:
> Yeah, thats the right one, but to make tf recognize the command, you must first
> type a '/send' so tf will execute:
> 
> /send kill blah %; fight blah %; engage stuff 

/send is irrelevant.  You still need to set %sub or use /eval.

"Andrew C.M. McClintock" <andrewm@tiger.hsc.edu> wrote:
> The only way to input multiple commands is to use the %; delimiter; this gets
> nasty/annoying because u have to reach with shift-key to the 5 key every
> time you want to do this.
> Here is some tf code i wrote to handle mutliple commands inputted at once,
> using the comma as a delimiter, and the ] and > keys as the commands
> trigger:
> 
> /alias ] /do_expand %{*}
> /alias > /eval /do_expand %%{$[strcat("dir_",%{1})]}%;\
>     /if ($[strlen(%{-1})]) /eval ] %{-1} %; /endif
> 
> /def -i do_expand = \
>         /let temp_str=%{*} %;\
>         /let commloc=$[strchr(temp_str,",")] %;\
>         /while ( commloc > -1 )\
>                 /let prev=$[substr(temp_str, 0, commloc)]%;\
>                 /let rest=$[substr(temp_str, $[commloc+1])]%;\
>                 /let temp_str=$[strcat(prev,"%;",rest)] %;\
>                 /let commloc=$[strchr(temp_str,",")] %;\
>         /done %;\
>         /eval %{temp_str}
> 
> 
> so usage would be:
> 
> ] s,kill dog,laugh dog,moon dog
> 
> the > functionality is for move macros, you have to set these before hand,
> like:
> 
> /set dir_temple s,e,n,w
> /set dir_somewhere e,s,w,n
> 
> > temple > somewhere
> 
> also you can use the move macros bundled with commands at the end:
> 
> > temple > somewhere kill dog,laugh dog,moon dog
> 
> this may or may not prove useful to you; i do welcome and critiques on the
> code and suggestions as to how i can make it faster...

This is not a bad idea, if you find "," more convenient than "%;".
But the implementation can be improved:

> /alias > /eval /do_expand %%{$[strcat("dir_",%{1})]}%;\
That $[...] expansion works, and would be needed for more complicated
expressions, but simple concatenation can be done with normal body expansion.
(Your use of /eval is correct, though).
>     /if ($[strlen(%{-1})]) /eval ] %{-1} %; /endif
There's no need for $[] inside () of an /if condition.
Inside an expression, {n} is better than %{n}.
Instead of using "/eval ] ...", just call /do_expand directly.

Improved version:

/alias > /eval /do_expand %%{dir_%{1}}%;\
    /if (strlen({-1})) /do_expand %{-1} %; /endif

> /def -i do_expand = \
>         /let temp_str=%{*} %;\
>         /let commloc=$[strchr(temp_str,",")] %;\
>         /while ( commloc > -1 )\
>                 /let prev=$[substr(temp_str, 0, commloc)]%;\
>                 /let rest=$[substr(temp_str, $[commloc+1])]%;\
There's no need to nest $[] inside $[].  (If you're unsure about grouping,
use (...), not $[...].)
>                 /let temp_str=$[strcat(prev,"%;",rest)] %;\
You don't need to stick them back together; just execute the stuff to the left
of the comma, and forget it.  Also, by concatenating them, you unnecessarily
re-scan the left side with each iteration.
>                 /let commloc=$[strchr(temp_str,",")] %;\
This duplicates code from line 3.  It can be moved into the /while condition
to avoid duplication.
>         /done %;\
>         /eval %{temp_str}

Improved version:

/def do_expand = \
    /let args=%*%; \
    /let i=0%; \
    /while ((i:=strchr(args, ",")) >= 0) \
        /eval $[substr(args, 0, i)]%; \
        /let args=$[substr(args, i+1)]%; \
    /done%; \
    /eval %args


