UNIX system passwords work in a "nobody can decrypt" because you've
always got the encryupted password to compare an encrypted version of
the typed in password to.

However, with TF, we need the plaintext, meaning that the means to 
decrypt must be in the system someplace.  That's a trivial crack,
in such a situation, unless you use something really strong like
RSA/etc.  And that'd mean typing in a password every time you start
TF, something that's easily snoopable by root.

Of course, I'm presuming you're concerned about getting rid of the
superuser's ability to snoop your passwords (if it's readonly to you,
then they're the only one to worry about).  Hell, even if the password
is encrypted with something strong, the root user could still dump
the start of any outbound TCP connection to port 4201 remote.  Name,
