runs a that program as a shell macro:

/def code = /IF ({#} >= 2) \
	/quote -dsend -w -1 !mpp %{-1} <%{1} %; \
	/ELSE /quote -dsend -w -1 !mpp < %{0} %; \
	/ENDIF

For quoting files, I have a (less pretty) macro (following) that works thus:

/sysquote page pooterbeast=,cat myfile

Generalized, that's:

/sysquote <MU* command>,<system command>

/def sysquote = /test regmatch('(,)',{0}) %; \
	/quote -dsend -w %PL ! %PR | \
		perl -pe 's/\%/\%\%/g; s/\\n/\%r/g ; s/\\s/\%b/g ; '

As far as something that will just arbitrarily munch newlines, you could 
do:

/def crunchlines = /quote -dsend -w ! %{0} | perl -pe 's/\\n//;' 

and then 

/crunchlines cat myfile

