I have recently encountered an interesting problem in tf 3.5b4.
I use redirection to get tf up and running with a few commands, start up a
connection to a MUD, and then let the triggers watch over the character.

This in itself is no problem.  The problem is that one of the triggers
disconnects from the MUD and then attempts to reconnect.  What happens is that
when the "startup" commands in the script to start tf are over, tf closes
standard input, as there is nothing else to read.  This makes fd 0 available
for other things, such as sockets.  socket() returns 0 on the next call, and tf
removes it from the fd_set, as it thinks it is standard input, and not a
socket.

I haven't looked at it much more than this, so I don't know how easy it would
be to fix.

One other little problem I've noticed:
in tf-lib/tintin.tf:

/def -i snoop   = \
                /if /ismacro _snoop_%1%; /then \
                        /@echo %% Snooping %1 disabled.%;\
                        /undef _snoop_%1%;\
                        /undef _snoopbg%1%;\
                /else \
                        /@echo %% Snooping %1 enabled.%;\
                        /def -i -w%1 -hbackground -ag _snoopbg_%1%;\
                        /def -i -t* -p9999 -w%1 -ag -F _snoop_%1 = \  
                                /@echo $${world_name}: %%*%;\
                /endif

There should be an underscore in the second /undef, to match the /def in the
definition below it.


