; assuming the last single quote would be the end of the line...
/def -i -mregexp -t" gossips 'How do I get to (.*)'$" catch_gossip = \
  /echo name: %PL %;\
  /echo destination: %P1

A few notes:
	1) I made it -i, so that it doesn't show up in /list, etc.
	2) I used double quotes for the -t part, so that you don't
	   have to escape out the single quote.
	3) I named the trigger.
	4) I put a space before "gossips" so that %PL (the name, I
	   assume), doesn't have a space in it when it gets to you.
	5) Using (.*) is kinda bad, as it's very general.  If you
	   don't mind having a single quote at the end of every
	   (valid) destination (you could fix this by always stripping
	   off the last character), then you could simplify the regexp
	   to:	" gossips 'How do I get to ". %PL would stay the same,
	   but %p1 would turn into, say: foo' instead of: foo

