Tinyfugue is originally a Unix utility.  It runs within a text-terminal.
This could be an ancient physical text-only terminal, such as an ADM3e
that I can see across the room from me and often use, or a terminal
emulator running within a graphical environment.  Just how is tinyfugue
supposed to provide a generic scrollbar utility?

When using rxvt or xterm under the X11 Windowing System (as I am now) one
does have scrollbars.  They're provided by the terminal emulator, not by
the application running within the terminal.  Other methods of
scrollback are provided.  Linux consoles, for example, have something
like shift-pageup/down to scroll through output.

For tinyfugue to provide scrollbars, it would have to open its own
window.  This would dramatically reduce its portability and usefulness
for many people.
