> Can somebody tell me what the rules for matching world
> types are?
> I discovered the other day that a world of type "tiny.mush.sye" will
> use hooks defined for type "tiny.mush", and I can't find
> documentation about this anywhere.  Are there any other tricks
> I could use?

The -T argument uses the -m argument (or %{matching} if none is explicitly
given) to decide whether a worldtype matches.  So, a trigger (or hook etc)
defined as -Ttiny.mush will run in worlds of type tiny.mush.foo,
tiny.mush.bar, tiny.mush, etc, _if_ regexp matching is used.  If you use
glob matching, then -Ttiny.mush* will run in the same worlds as above.

I use this worldtype matching mechanism to restrict triggers in worlds where
I have 'alt' characters:

/addworld -Ttiny.muck ...  (normal world)
/addworld -Ttiny.mux ... (another normal world)
/addworld -Ttiny.muck.notrig ... (world where I have an alt)

/def -p95 -mglob -Ttiny*.notrig -t'*' block_notrig

.. where I have most of my triggers defined as priorities <100, but hilites
>100.


