Yes, assuming that your first trigger is something like this:

/def -p200 -F -t'some pattern' mud_trigger = \
    /trigger LOCAL some text


You can do this:

/def local_substitute = /set lsub_var=%*

/def -p200 -F -t'some pattern' mud_trigger = \
    /local_substitute %*%;\
    /trigger LOCAL some text%;\
    /substitute %{lsub_var}

And use /local_substitute in your local triggers.

Also, I strongly recommend that instead of prefixing with `LOCAL', that
instead you make a dummy world, and have the local_trigger in that world 
and use /trigger -w.  ${world_name} and similar maintain their original
values, so it doesn't change any existing behaviour you have.


/addworld local localhost echo
/histsize -wlocal 10

/def local_substitute = /set lsub_var=%*

/def -p200 -F -t'some pattern' mud_trigger = \
    /local_substitute %*%;\
    /trigger -wlocal some text%;\
    /substitute %{lsub_var}

/def -p501 -wlocal -F -t'^(.*)$' local_trigger = \
    /local_substitute %P1



