Why do you use /eval here?  It's a bad habit to use /eval when it's not
needed, since it will bite you some day.

If you are using 4.0, histsize used as an expression function returns
the number of lines.  So you can restore the world to the same amount of 
history that it previously had.

/def clear_hist =\
    /quote -S /: `/clear_hist_ %1

/def clear_hist_ =
    /let old_size=$[histsize("-w%1")]%;\
    /histsize -w%1 1%;\
    /recordline -w%1%;
    /histsize -w%1 %{old_size}

Where the /quote /: `/foo or a  /: $(...) will eat the output you don't
care about.


You could also just /unworld the world and /addworld it again.  Which
will also start renumbering the history at 1 again, unlike the resizing
approach above.

