Overlapping attributes are added together.

> Also, is there any way to include \ in a regexp? I have tried \\, but that
> don't work.

In a case like /def -t"...", there are two levels of escaping required.

First, the quotes for the -t"..." option allow \" (for literal ") or \\
(for literal \) inside the string.  Any other use of \ is in a quoted
string is technically incorrect (tf will usually do what you expect with
those other uses, but you shouldn't depend on it).

Second, metacharacters in a regexp must be prefixed with \, and to produce
a literal \, you must use \\.

So, to get a literal \ in a regexp you must use \\, and then to get that
literal \\ in a quoted string you must use \\\\.  Therefore a regexp trigger
on a literal \ would be defined like this:

  /def -t"\\\\" ...

