> I need the two /eval's to fix the variable names in those lines, but
> they mess up the rest of the function too unless I double all the 
> remaining %%s - which I don't want to do.

You end an /eval just like you end any other command; in macro body, you
do it with "%;".  Each "%" you intend to be part of the /eval'd text
needs to be written as "%%"; that means "%;" must be written "%%;".
Your second /eval doesn't belong there, and every "%" you have needs to
be changed to "%%", except for the "%%*" which you got right.

Style note:  "%" is not necessary in expressions, and since it often leads
to confusion when multiple eval levels are involved, it's best to avoid it:

  /def -T"irc" say = \
     /eval /if (channel_${world_name} !~ "") \
  ...

You can avoid the /eval ugliness when using /if or /while, by using /test
instead of (), because /test evals its arguments:

  /def -T"irc" say = \
     /if /test channel_${world_name} !~ ""%; \
        /eval /send -w PRIVMSG %%{channel_${world_name}} :%%*%; \
        /if (irc_display_mode =~ "mud") \
           /trigger LOCAL  You say, "%*"%; \
        /else \
           /trigger LOCAL <%{irc_nick}> %*%; \
        /endif %;\
     /else \
        /trigger LOCAL %{irc_error_prefix} You're not on a channel!%; \
     /endif

