I want TF to write certain lines of text to disk, where an external
program has to analyse the text immediately.

First I tried 'fwrite'. This worked fine so far, but had the disadvantage
of a relative large overhead, because it openes and closes the file for
every line of text it writes.

Therefore I tested 'tfwrite'. The overhead was reduced to a minimum,
because I had to open and close the file only one time each evening.

The problem is that output with 'tfwrite' is buffered. The whole text is
buffered in memory until the file is closed or the (relative large)
buffer is full. Thus the external program can't analyse the 'written' text
immediately, but has to wait, until the internal buffer is flushed.

One possibility is to close the file each time I want the external program
to analyse the new text. This would be the same as using 'fwrite'. The
other possibility is to cry for a new command ;-)

Therefore I would like to suggest a new command 'tfflush(handle)'. The
only task of this command is to flush the internal buffers for file
(handle) immediately and write the text to disk without closing the file.


