This turns out to be a particular bad suggestion in this case.  First of 
all %| won't help you here particuarly, and secondly it'll point you
encourage a wild goose chase through some of the more complicated parts
of tf4.0.

Short answer, use /quote -S to call out to host.

Something like this (which is just to give an idea):

/def -t'^([12]?[0-9]?[0-9]\\.[12]?[0-9]?[0-9]\\.[12]?[0-9]?[0-9]\\.[12]?[0-9]?[0-9]) +([^ ]* +)' match_people =\
    /let ip=%{P1}%:\
    /let hostname=%;\
    /let who=%{P2}%;\
    /quote -S /collect_host_name !host %{ip}%;\
    /substitute -- %{ip} %{who} %{hostname}

/def collect_host_name =\
    /test hostname := %5

You'll notice that I collect the extra spaces after the player name with
``([^ ]* +)'' so that the hostname can be indented correctly.  You could
also just go with [0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+ for the ip address
if you want too.


