> this
> /def x = /send prompt >*\b\377\371

TF does not interpret those '\' sequences as control characters; to TF,
the '\' means ignore the special meaning (if any) of the next character.
So when /x is called, the command that gets executed is:
  /send prompt >*b377371

TF expects either asterisk backspace _or_ IAC GOAHEAD, not both.

If the mud is implemented correctly, and you set your prompt to include
IAC GOAHEAD, the mud will actually send IAC IAC GOAHEAD, which is not what
you want.

If your mud interprets '\b' as backspace, the command you want is:
  /send prompt >*\b
and a macro that will generate that command is:
  /def x = /send prompt >*\\b

If your mud does not interpret '\b' as backspace, but does accept control
characters, your command will have to send the actual control character.
One way to do that is by executing this version of /x:
  /def x = /send prompt >*$[char(8)]

Once you convince your mud to send asterisk backslash at the end of each
prompt, you can /set lp=off in tf.

