That version of strreverse is not very efficient; I made it simple to use
as an example for "/help return".  As anyone who has taken an algorithms
class can tell you, that algorithm has a recursion depth proportional to
N (where N is the length of the string), so it doesn't take a very large
string to overflow tf's internal stack.  The version below is much smarter:
it splits the string in half each time and recurses on that, so the recusion
depth is proportional to log2(N) (which I estimate will only overflow tf's
stack for strings more than about 4 trillion characters, and you'll run
out of other resources long before you create a string that large).

/def strreverse = \
    /let len=$[strlen({*})]%; \
    /return (len <= 1) ? {*} : \
        strcat(strreverse(substr({*},len/2)), strreverse(substr({*},0,len/2)))

With this version, I successfully reversed a string of length 27599 (which
took 20 seconds on a 166MHz Pentium).


By the way, the iterative version below took 93 seconds on the same long
string (and required increasing the value of %max_iter).

/def strreverse = \
    /let i=$[strlen({*})]%; \
    /let result=%; \
    /while (--i >= 0) \
        /test result:=strcat(result, substr({*},i,1))%; \
    /done%; \
    /return result

