It took me a while to figure out why this is a problem, but the answer's
really rather simple: the new C standard (C9X as it's being called now, or the
second ANSI revision of C) defines a keyword 'restrict' that recommends to the
compiler that taking an alias to a particular pointer should not be allowed,
or something of the sort. To my eyes, it's about as useful as the 'register'
and 'auto' keywords, but I have yet to see it used in experience.

I'm not sure how to solve this, exactly. The simplest method would probably be
to replace all occurances of 'restrict' with some variant ('re_strict' or
